Negative Space of Subtraction
Subtraction is an operation subject to relation between numbers, such as distance.
Space of Addition & Subtraction form a complete system.
Subtraction is necessary to establish the relational operators of the numeric foundation of order
	{  >, <, = }
A - B > 0 establishes relation (A > B) = (B < A)
A - B = 0 establishes the relation of A = B.

An unbounded sequence of subtraction traverses the numeric-continuum in an expansion in the negative direction.
A system must be balanced. The expansion in the positive direction equal to the expansion in the negative direction.

The universe denies any fixed universal origin. 
The mathematical measure of systems & relations requires the origin of the continuum to be adaptable to the situation.
Negative space is consequent to the translation of the origin in a system. 
Negative space uniquely allows symmetry of structure with respect to the origin.

Elements of negative space do not require elements of positive space to change directions from negative to positive. Positive elements require elements of negative space to change direction from positive to negative.

Certain situations void negative space: measure, distance, denomination.
Negative numbers have no even-powered roots.
The mathematician must use great care in working in negative space.
Positive space is natural, but negative space is a relative idea that has no natural anchor.

Ancient Greeks did not believe in negative space.
They focused their study upon analysis of the individual structure.

Modern mathematics expanded to measure systems. 
Systems require adaptable origin to maintain structural-based relationships.
Negative space arises from the translation of the origin demanded by the situation.

Mathematics is the science of measure. 
Measurement is always under dominion of the situation.
The situation dictates the translation of the origin.
Certain systems require a shift from natural space to negative space, this transformation forces the symmetry of negative space.
The elemental characteristics of natural space are nullified by superposition of characteristics of negative space.
A positive element is stripped of all characteristics, retaining only magnitude. This magnitude is then adorned with all the characteristics of a negative element.
Dimensional Space of Multiplication
